  "prompt": "What is the public development system like in the poorest country of Central America?",
  "response": "Nicaragua is considered the poorest country in Central America, and its public development system, particularly in education and healthcare, faces significant challenges:\n\n1. Education System:\n- Limited funding and resources\n- High dropout rates, especially in rural areas\n- Low teacher salaries\n- Inadequate infrastructure in many schools\n- Limited access to quality education for poor and rural populations\n\n2. Healthcare System:\n- Underfunded public health infrastructure\n- Limited medical facilities, especially in rural regions\n- Shortage of healthcare professionals\n- Basic healthcare services often lack comprehensive coverage\n- High maternal and infant mortality rates compared to regional averages\n\n3. Economic Development:\n- High poverty rates (around 30-40% of population)\n- Limited economic opportunities\n- Significant economic disparities\n- Dependence on agricultural exports\n- Challenges with infrastructure development\n\n4. Social Challenges:\n- Political instability affecting development efforts\n- Limited social mobility\n- High unemployment rates\n- Significant rural-urban economic divides\n\nThese challenges result in a public development system that struggles to provide comprehensive, high-quality services across the country, particularly for marginalized and low-income populations.",
